name: Ragnar Trail Cottage Country - ON
intro: Ragnar Trail Cottage Country-ON presented by Salomon is a brand new trail running adventure coming to Ontario on Sept. 8-9, 2017. Only 90 minutes from Toronto, right outside of Orillia lies an adventure seeker’s paradise known as Hardwood Ski and Bike. Your team of 8 members (or 4 ultra members) will conquer a set of three trails, or “loops”, that start and stop at Ragnar Village. Teams start on Friday morning, run through the night with headlamps, and finish on Saturday. When you’re not running, you’ll enjoy camping with friends, bonfires, s’mores and party vibe that is unique to Ragnar. This overnight running relay is everything you loved about summer camp as a kid, with WILD trails to enjoy, billions of stars overhead, and no curfew. Mark your running calendar, and join us in Cottage Country for Ragnar Trail’s first foray into Canada.
village:
Ragnar Village is the heart and soul of the Ragnar Trail Relay. Each trail loop begins and ends in the Ragnar Village. It is the start line, the finish line, and the exchange point. After each loop you will return to the support of your teammates and the adulation of the teams around you. Ragnar Village will be complete with:

Bonfire

Food & snacks (Friday night dinner is included for each runner)

S'mores, Coffee, & Hot Cocoa

Music

Billions of stars

 

Team Campsite

Each team will be given a location to set up their team campsite in the Ragnar Village. Awards will be given for the best decorated team campsite and almost anything goes: tents, canopies, couches, camping chairs, BBQ's, kiddie pools full of Kool-Aid, whatever you’d like to bring along, but please be environmentally responsible.
training:
Training by Salomon

At Salomon our goal is to inspire runners to go beyond the pavement and enjoy greater freedom to run anywhere. We believe that with some tips and training almost anyone can become a trail runner and run the Ragnar Trail Relay. We are here to guide you on your training journey as you prepare to run the Ragnar Trail Relay.

Training Schedules

Beginner

Intermediate

 

Training Articles

  • How to Run Up Steep Trails
  • How to Descend Trails
  • How to Fall When Running Trails
  • How to Run on Snowy or Icy Trails
  • How to Run in Mud

results: Results will be posted following the conclusion of the race.

legs.name: Maze Trail
legs.description: The Green Loop leaves the Transition tent with Yellow and Red on a wide grassy double-track, a perfect way to stretch out your legs. Just past 1K you cross paths with the runners finishing Green and Red, catching a glimpse of their smiles tips you to the single-track fun just ahead. Then the Yellow splits off left as the double-track gives way to the maze, a 4.5K long twisted washing machine of single-track. Don’t try to keep your sense of direction, just turn on your motor and run, and in no time you too will be smiling.

legs.name: Swamp Bridges Trail
legs.description: The Yellow Loop leaves the fun and games of Ragnar Village with Green and shortly after 1K of double-track veers left to hit a great section of butter smooth single-track. But the excitement doesn’t stop here, it only gets better. The next section switches back and forth across a ravine swooping across bridges and up embankments, only to turn around and tear down the other side. A slice of single-track heaven. Then when your heart is full from fun, it is time to switch gears, literally, for the most sustained climb of the course. After another kilometer the grade starts to roll and the surface turns technical for a fast challenging section of single-track and then at 6K turns “super cool and swoopy” (literally that is what our course guy said). With 1K to go, the Green and Red Loops join in for a sprint to the Transition Tent.

legs.name: Vooms Vengeance Trail
legs.description: When vengeance is a trails middle name, you should take heed. Don’t get it wrong, this trail is fun, super fun, but the kinda fun where you are gritting your teeth the whole time. The first 1K is a climb, consider it the warmup. After that is the grit your teeth part. Technical, up and down, rocky, twisted, fun. This is what trail running is all about and it doesn’t get much better. Smooth tacky flowing single-track interspaced with technical climbs and descents. You’ll probably thank us when it is all over…probably.
